<div class="welcome-container">
    <h2>Understanding Private Fund Secondary Sales</h2>
    <p>
        Private fund investments are typically long-term and illiquid, but UBS offers a structured secondary market framework that can provide liquidity through internal peer-to-peer transactions. This guide explains how you, as an individual investor on the UBS platform, can sell or buy a private fund position from another UBS client.
    </p>

    <h2>What is a Secondary Market Transaction?</h2>
    <p>
        A secondary market transaction allows an investor to sell their interest in a private fund (such as a private equity or venture capital fund) to another investor. This provides liquidity when needed without waiting for the fund to fully liquidate.
    </p>

    <h2>How It Works</h2>
    <p>The following steps outline a typical peer-to-peer transaction between UBS clients.</p>
    
    <div class="steps-list">
        <ol>
            <li>Investor A decides to sell their interest in a private fund.</li>
            <li>Investor B expresses interest in purchasing the fund interest.</li>
            <li>Investor A's Private Banker provides recent fund details including Net Asset Value (NAV) and other relevant information and facilitates pricing guidance with Investor A.</li>
            <li>Investor B contacts their Private Banker to discuss an offer.</li>
            <li>Investor B's Private Banker coordinates documentation, including Purchase and Sale Agreements and Transfer Agreements.</li>
            <li>Upon approval by Investor A and Investor B, the transaction is executed and settled within the Firm's custody systems.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

